- a backgrounded command followed by more commands on the *same input
  line* either mis-parses or crashes the shell outright, found while
  re-testing the "{ cmd; } &" fix below: "true & echo after" (a single
  line passed via -c) segfaults the shell itself (confirmed pre-
  existing on a clean checkout, not a regression); "{ true; } & echo
  after" instead gives a parse error, "unexpected token NAME", right
  after the "}". Putting the next command on its own line (a real
  newline instead of continuing after "&") works fine in both cases,
  so this is specific to same-line "&"-then-more parsing, not
  backgrounding itself
- tests/posix/fnmatch-p.tst hangs the testee (100% CPU spin), found via
  the same conformance-suite run that found the "eval continue" hang
  below; not yet isolated to a specific case within the file
- the fdtable resolver (fdtable_resolve/fdtable_close/fdtable_dup/...)
  has no real cycle detection, only a defensive depth cap added later;
  a genuinely cyclic redirection still fails instead of resolving, root
  cause (why the recursion can happen at all) is untouched
- arithmetic expansion containing a variable name fails to parse:
  "echo $((i+1))" prints the literal "i+1" followed by "unexpected
  token )" and exit 1 (same for $(( i + 1 )) and in assignments,
  "i=$((i+1))"); constant-only arithmetic like "echo $((1+1))" works.
  found while trying to write a while-loop repro -- any POSIX script
  using the idiomatic i=$((i+1)) counter dies on this
- builtin_wait (src/builtin/builtin_wait.c) always "return 0;" no
  matter what the waited-for job(s) actually exited with -- it captures
  job_wait()'s status into a local variable and never uses it. Found
  while checking that the WAIT_EXITSTATUS fix actually surfaces through
  "wait": confirmed live, "sh -c 'exit 42' & wait; echo $?" prints 0
  instead of 42. Separately, "$!" (the last background PID) isn't
  implemented at all -- always expands empty
- running this repo's own ./configure under shish still duplicates
  blocks of output and dies at AC_PROG_CC with a false "C compiler
  cannot create executables" (gcc works); with the fdtable_dup
  dup-storm fixed, configure now runs that far in seconds instead of
  burning the whole fd table -- the remaining suspects are the
  duplicated-output/re-execution bug (command substitution of a
  pipeline also returns an empty string and runs the surrounding
  command twice: 'x=`echo hi | sed 1q`; echo "[$x]"' prints "[]"
  twice) and the fdstack_push assertion below. the MinSizeRel build
  behaves differently from Debug on the same configure: pre-fix its
  forked children died with SEGV at address 0x10 where Debug stormed,
  and post-fix it bails at the as_myself check ("configure: error:
  cannot find myself") where Debug proceeds to AC_PROG_CC -- $0 and
  "case $0 in *[\\/]*)" work fine in isolation on both builds, so
  something earlier in configure corrupts state only in the
  optimized build; worth an asan build to catch what Debug tolerates
- FIXED: a pipeline inside a subshell used to leak its builtin members
  as extra copies of the interpreter -- "(true | true)" made everything
  after the subshell run 3 times. Root cause: eval_pipeline() forks a
  real child per pipeline member and expects sh_exit() (invoked via
  the E_EXIT-flagged eval_tree() call, wrapped in "exit(...)") to
  really terminate that child. But sh_exit()/eval_exit() longjmp back
  to the nearest jump-enabled `struct eval` frame instead of exiting
  whenever one is on the (global) `eval` chain -- and a subshell
  (eval_subshell()) pushes exactly such a frame via setjmp(), which
  survives fork() as a still-valid stack address in the child's copy
  of the stack. The forked child's sh_exit() found that inherited
  frame and longjmped back into eval_subshell() *inside the child*,
  which then returned normally into the top-level eval_tree() loop --
  so the "exited" child kept interpreting the rest of the script as a
  second full copy of the shell. Fixed in sh_forked() (called from
  every fork path, job_fork() included) by clearing `jump` on every
  frame in the inherited `eval` chain right after forking, so
  eval_exit() never finds a target and sh_exit() always falls through
  to a real exit() in a forked child. This is the fix the file already
  half-attempted: sh_forked() had "// sh->eval->jump = 0;" commented
  out, targeting the wrong variable (sh->eval is never actually
  updated -- eval_push()/eval_pop() maintain a separate global `eval`)
  and only the top frame besides.
- FIXED: the PATH search (exec_path.c) and exec_hash()'s direct-path
  branch (name containing "/") both checked candidates with nothing
  but access(path, X_OK), so a DIRECTORY matched (directories are
  "executable" as in searchable); POSIX requires an executable regular
  file. Bit for real: with emscripten's SDK dir on PATH, "test"
  resolved to emsdk/test/ (a directory) and shadowed /usr/bin/test --
  which was exactly why tests/builtin-test.sh failed on builds
  configured with BUILTIN_TEST=OFF (the cfg'd build/x86_64-linux-gnu)
  while default builds passed. Fixed by adding an S_ISDIR check after
  access() succeeds in both exec_path() (skip and keep searching PATH)
  and exec_hash() (reject, matching what execve() itself reports).
- FIXED: exec failure exit statuses and messages were wrong in both
  halves of the exec path. Parent half (PATH/path lookup failing
  before anything is even forked): always exited 1 where POSIX wants
  127 (not found) / 126 (found but not executable) -- exec_error()'s
  ENOENT/EACCES mapping was only ever invoked from the post-fork
  execve() path, and separately the message hardcoded
  strerror(ENOENT) regardless of what actually went wrong ("shish -c
  /etc/hostname" said "No such file or directory" for a file that
  exists but isn't executable). Fixed by having exec_hash()/exec_path()
  record the real errno from the failing access()/stat() into a new
  `exec_lasterrno` (plain "errno" isn't trustworthy -- redirections,
  variable expansion etc. all run between the lookup and the message,
  and routinely clobber it), and having eval_simple_command.c's "not
  found" branch use that instead of a hardcoded ENOENT. exec_error()
  also didn't map EISDIR/ENOEXEC to 126, relevant now that directory
  matches are correctly rejected rather than silently accepted. Child
  half (execve() itself failing post-fork on a path that passed every
  pre-check, e.g. a chmod +x'd file that isn't actually a valid
  executable -> ENOEXEC): the forked child SEGV'd handling its own
  error, and the "silent success, status 0" originally reported was
  really that SEGV's exit status getting silently swallowed somewhere
  on the way back through job_wait (a directory match specifically
  looked fine only because the parent-side PATH-search fix above now
  intercepts it before it ever reaches this path). Root cause:
  fdtable_exec() -- called right before execve(), on the assumption
  that a successful exec makes cleanup moot -- pops every pushed
  source off the source stack, but exec_program()'s post-execve()
  failure handler still unconditionally calls sh_error_errno() ->
  sh_msgn() -> source_msg(), which dereferenced
  fdtable[STDSRC_FILENO]->name assuming a source was still there.
  Fixed source_msg() to fall back to sh_name (matching what it already
  does when a source has no name of its own) when no source is
  pushed. Separately, once that no longer crashed, the message lost
  its strerror() text and the exit status still came out wrong:
  exec_error() (called right before sh_error_errno() in
  exec_program.c) zeroes errno as its very last step, and
  sh_error_errno()'s own buffer_puts()/write() calls are free to leave
  errno changed too (POSIX only guarantees it's preserved on failure,
  not success) -- so by either path, whichever of the two ran second
  was reading a clobbered value. Fixed by saving errno once, right
  after execve() returns, and using that saved copy for both the
  message and the status mapping instead of a live "errno" that nothing
  else in this function should have been trusting in the first place.
- "for x in \"$@\"; do ...; done" fails to parse when positional
  params include a quoted empty string: 'set -- -n ""; for a in
  "$@"; do echo "[$a]"; done' gives "unexpected token EOF, expecting
  'done'" instead of looping twice. Found chasing a
  tests/builtin-test.sh failure on the BUILTIN_TEST=OFF build ("test
  -n \"\"" resolving to a lost second argument, so /usr/bin/test saw
  only "-n" and reported the single-argument-string-test true instead
  of the intended empty-string-is-false result) -- "$#" alone reports
  the right count (2) for the same "set --", so the params themselves
  are intact; the parser chokes specifically on iterating "$@" in a
  for-loop when one element is empty
- fdstack_push() (src/fdstack/fdstack_push.c:8) can hit its own
  consistency assertion, "st < fdstack || fdstack == &fdstack_root",
  under heavy nested command-substitution + subshell use; confirmed
  with tests/param.sh under asan (a script that's mostly repeated
  "assert_equal ... $(...)" calls). Confirmed pre-existing, not a
  regression: reproduces identically on a clean checkout via a
  separate worktree. Non-asan builds don't hit the assertion but the
  underlying corruption is still there -- tests/param.sh's last
  assertion silently evaluates to the wrong value ('0' instead of the
  expected string) instead of crashing
- backgrounding a non-simple (compound) command, e.g. "{ cmd; } &",
  still duplicates its execution and corrupts what follows -- NOT
  actually fixed by the branch flip committed as c039280e: that flip
  corrected which process runs eval_node()+exit(), but the parent then
  falls through to the unconditional "ret = eval_node(e, node)" at
  eval_tree.c:50 and runs the same compound a second time itself, and
  the "job_wait(job, pid, &st)" in the bgnd block makes the parent
  wait synchronously for a job that's supposed to be background;
  repro unchanged: "{ sleep 1; echo bg_done; } & echo after_bg; wait;
  echo end" prints "bg_done" twice and never reaches
  "after_bg"/"end", with a spurious parse error in between
- "export FOO" (or any way of marking a variable for export before
  it's ever assigned a value) followed by "export -p" or bare "export"
  segfaults: var_print() (src/var/var_print.c) unconditionally does
  buffer_put(fd_out->w, var->sa.s, var->len) to print the name, but
  var->sa.s is NULL until the variable is actually assigned
  (var_init() only stralloc_init()s it); the guard that was clearly
  meant to prevent this, "if(!(var->flags & V_UNSET))", never fires
  because V_UNSET (src/var.h) is declared and checked but nothing in
  the codebase ever sets it
- ">&-"/"<&-" (closing a file descriptor) doesn't really close.
  For the shell's own builtins fd_null() silently redirects it to a
  null sink, so e.g. "exec 3>&-; echo hi >&3" exits 0 with no error in
  shish where every POSIX shell (bash included) reports "Bad file
  descriptor" and exits 1. For external commands it's broken on stdin
  at least: "cat <&-" leaves fd 0 pointing at the shell's own stdin
  (hangs on a terminal/pipe stdin where bash's cat gets EBADF and
  exits 1), and combining it with a preceding redirect, "cat < infile
  <&-", silently drops the infile redirect too -- cat reads the
  shell's original stdin (repro: 'shish -c "cat < infile <&-" < outer'
  prints outer's contents; bash prints nothing and exits 1)
- PATH reassignment doesn't invalidate the remembered command-search
  cache (POSIX 3.9.1.1 requires it to): confirmed live against bash --
  "PATH=/a:$PATH; cmd; PATH=/b:$PATH; cmd" runs /a's cmd both times in
  shish, but correctly switches to /b's cmd the second time in bash;
  exec_search()/the exec hash never gets invalidated on a PATH=
  assignment
- builtin echo rejects any unrecognized word starting with "-" as an
  "invalid option" instead of printing it as an operand: "echo -x" and
  "echo ---foo" both error and exit 1 in shish, print the word in
  bash/every POSIX shell (found because a test script doing "echo
  ---marker---" died on it)
- builtin_fg (src/builtin/builtin_jobs.c) has a stack out-of-bounds
  write for the common no-argument case: "struct job *joblist[njobs]"
  is sized argc-1 (0 for bare "fg"), then joblist[0] is written anyway;
  confirmed crash under asan (dynamic-stack-buffer-overflow)
- fg/bg don't implement job control's stop/resume half: fg never calls
  job_foreground() (never called from anywhere) so it doesn't actually
  hand over the terminal, never sends SIGCONT, and busy-waits via
  wait_pids_nohang() instead of blocking; bg (builtin_bg) is an empty
  stub; there is no SIGCONT anywhere and no kill builtin, so a
  Ctrl-Z-stopped job can't be resumed at all
- wait_nohang() (lib/wait/wait_nohang.c) has no return statement on its
  WINDOWS_NATIVE branch, undefined behavior; it drives the SIGCHLD
  handler in sh_main.c, so child reaping is broken on native windows
- sig_push() (lib/sig/sig_push.c) reinterprets sigset_t (a 128-byte
  struct on glibc) through an unsigned long*, undefined behavior;
  currently harmless only because the function is unused
- sh_onsig(), the SIGCHLD handler in sh_main.c, calls
  term_erase()/term_restore()/buffered i/o directly from signal-handler
  context; none of that is async-signal-safe
- job_free()'s job_delete() sets job_pointer to NULL when the current
  job is deleted instead of promoting the previous job to current (bash
  promotes "-" to "+"), so the "+"-marked job just disappears once it
  finishes
